Introduction and Brief Problem Description¶

For my final analysis project, I am using the Abalone data from UC Irvine Machine Learning Repository. My grandparents lived near the coast in northern California, USA, and I have fond memories of meals made from the abalone he harvested.

Abalone are a shellfish which live in the crevices of rocky reefs or in kelp beds. They grow slowly; it can take 12 years to reach 7 inches in diameter, which is small for an abalone. This makes them vulnerable to overfishing because it takes so many years to replace each abalone taken. (https://wildlife.ca.gov/Conservation/Marine/Invertebrates/Abalone)

Determining the age of an abalone is similar to finding the age of a tree; the shell is cut and the rings are counted. In the case of abalone, however, the rings must first be stained and then counted through a microscope. This is a time consuming process, so the goal of this data analysis is to find a way to determine age using other measurements which can be collected more efficiently.

We see that one feature is categorical and the others are continuous, and there is no missing data. Within that categorical variable, there are three categories, and from the size of the categories, it is important to keep all three classes. For this analysis, we will use the original data for linear regression, restrict to non-categorical when building a KNN model, and finally we use one hot encoding on the categorical variable when building models with decision tree and random forest algorithms. We will use an 80/20 split for our training data and testing data.

In [3]:
random.seed(100)

# For when we use a training set and testing set
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test= train_test_split(X,y, test_size = 0.20)

# Resetting indices prevents concatenation issues when we do the one hot encoding
X_train.reset_index(drop = True, inplace = True)
X_test.reset_index(drop = True, inplace = True)
y_train.reset_index(drop = True, inplace = True)
y_test.reset_index(drop = True, inplace = True)

# Removing the categorical variable for use with KNN
X_train_numeric = X_train.drop(columns = ['Sex'])
X_test_numeric = X_test.drop(columns = ['Sex'])

# For computing accuracy and mean squared error
ytr = np.array(y_train.Rings)
yte = np.array(y_test.Rings)

Analysis¶

We will begin with linear regression to create a baseline, consider k-nearest numbers, and finally model with decision trees and random forests.

Linear Regression¶

None of our EDA leads us to think Linear Regression is the best path because of the high correlation between variables, but a linear model provides a good baseline for future methods.

Our first model includes all the predictors.

With all the correlation between variables, it is reasonable to ask whether using a single variable would suffice. Here are the adjusted R^2 and TMSE for all models build on a single feature. But these result in a decreased adjusted R^2 and an increase in TMSE.

In [13]:
for col_name in X_train.columns:
    f = 'Rings ~ ' + col_name
    lmod1 = smf.ols(formula = f, data = df).fit()
    yp = np.array(lmod1.predict(X_test))
    TMSE = sum((yp - yte)**2)/len(yp)
    print(round(lmod1.rsquared_adj,4), ' and ', round(TMSE,4), 'are the adjusted R^2 and ' \
          'TMSE respectively for a linear model with predictor', col_name )

Regression with interactions and polynomial terms¶

The relation between rings and shell-weight appeared to have a square-root or cube-root relation. There is also likely important interaction between variables.

In [14]:
# Best model with two features
lmod2 = smf.ols(formula = 'Rings ~ Shell_weight + Diameter', data = df).fit()
yp = np.array(lmod2.predict(X_test))
TMSE = sum((yp - yte)**2)/len(yp)
print(round(lmod2.rsquared_adj,4), ' and ', round(TMSE,4), 'are the adjusted R^2 and TMSE respectively '
      'for a linear model with predictors Shell_weight and Diameter')

# Interaction model with two most descriptive features
lmod_int = smf.ols(formula = 'Rings ~ Shell_weight* Diameter', data = df).fit()
yp = np.array(lmod_int.predict(X_test))
TMSE = sum((yp - yte)**2)/len(yp)
print(round(lmod_int.rsquared_adj,4), ' and ', round(TMSE,4), 'are the adjusted R^2 and TMSE respectively '
      'for a linear model with predictors Shell_weight and Diameter with an interaction term.' )

# Model inspired by the fact that rings visibly looks like it varies with a fractional power of Shell_weight
lmod_root = smf.ols(formula = 'Rings ~ Shell_weight + I(Shell_weight**0.5)', data = df).fit()
yp = np.array(lmod_root.predict(X_test))

print(round(lmod_root.rsquared_adj,4), ' and ', round(TMSE,4), 'are the adjusted R^2 and TMSE respectively '
      'for a linear model with cube root of Shell_weight.' )

# Polynomial model for completeness

TMSE = sum((yp - yte)**2)/len(yp)
print(round(lmod_poly.rsquared_adj,4), ' and ', round(TMSE,4), 'are the adjusted R^2 and TMSE respectively '
      'for a polynomial model cubic in Shell_weight')

I tried other combinations, but the winning model for this section remained the model with 'Rings ~ Diameter + Height + Whole_weight + Shucked_weight + Viscera_weight + Shell_weight'.

KNN (Numeric Data Only)¶

Now, let's consider a k-nearest neighbor model. Because KNN uses a metric, and I'm not ready to create a custom metric to resolve the categorical data differences, I am just going to use the numeric data and ignore the categorical feature 'Sex' for the KNN models.

The main hyper-parameter in KNN is the number of neighbors, k. We can run a loop to tune the model.

In [15]:
MSE_train = []
MSE_test = []

for k in range(2,60):
    knn = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=k, weights='uniform', 
                                       algorithm='auto', leaf_size=30, p=2, 
                                       metric='minkowski', metric_params=None, n_jobs=None)
    knn_model = knn.fit(X_train_numeric, y_train)
    yp = np.array(knn_model.predict(X_train_numeric))
    yt = np.array(y_train.Rings)
    MSE_knn_model = np.mean((yp.reshape(1,-1) - yt)**2)
    #print(k, 'The training mean squared error is', MSE_knn_model)
    MSE_train.append(MSE_knn_model)
    yp = np.array(knn_model.predict(X_test_numeric))
    yt = np.array(y_test.Rings)
    TMSE_knn_model = np.mean((yp.reshape(1,-1) - yt)**2)
    #print(k, 'The test mean squared error is', TMSE_knn_model)
    MSE_test.append(TMSE_knn_model)

# Plot of errors    
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1,ncols=1,figsize=(12,7))
ax.plot(range(2,60), MSE_train, marker="o", color="steelblue", lw=3, label = "train")
#ax.plot(range(2,60), MSE_test, marker="o", color="red", lw=3, label = "test")
ax.set_xlabel("number k of neighbors", fontsize=16)
ax.set_ylabel("Mean Squared Error", fontsize=16)
plt.xticks(range(1,60,1))
ax.legend()
ax.grid(alpha=0.25)

Based on these results, I would choose k=24 for the best fit. Without the test data and with just the training data, because that is the location where growth in the mean squared error really plateuas. I did compute test MSE, and here is that plot. Maybe a lower k, say k = 20, would be slightly better, but I'm sticking with my original decision.

During exploration, I did also build models where I normalize the inputs, but that made no marked difference in the mean squared errors. I also tried different metrics, and the L-3 metric showed slightly better performance, but again not enough to justify changing the metric.

Decision Tree Models¶

A decision tree model seems like a natural model for this type of data, where there are three distinct categories for one of the features. As a reminder, scikit learn does not accept categorical variables in the "DecisionTreeRegressor" and "RandomForestRegressor" classes, so I used one hot encoding for the categorical variable.

The one-hot encoding replaced the categries M, F and I in the categorical column 'Sex' by the 3-tuples (0,0,1), (1,0,0) and (0,1,0) respectively. If we wanted to do linear regression with this data, we would need to delete one of the columns to avoid collinearity, but decision tree models and random forest models can be fed all three columns.

Random Forests¶

And here we are finally at Random Forests. I hope we took the correct shortcuts on the journey to get here. First, I'm running a model using all of the default parameters. Already we see that improvement over the single decision tree in test MSE, but the low training MSE warns us to be aware of overfitting.

In [20]:
rfr = RandomForestRegressor()

The training mean squared error is 0.6608273271475607
The test mean squared error is 5.0013811004784685

In this analysis, which I wrote for a class and in which I wanted to show progression, I started with the most basic supervised models, linear models, and used a very unsophisticated tuning method of "guess and check". For the more flexible knn, I used a more sophisticated tuning method, manually creating a "grid" and loop to check different parameter values. These methods are not typically used by data scientists in practice. Because we are at the final type of model, we are going to use support programs, in particular k-fold cross validation and a grid search, to tune our Random Forest Regressor.

Conclusion¶

In this analysis, I build a linear regression model, "Linear," using rudimentary techniques to choose which features to include. Then, I built a KNN model, "KNN" with tuning only on the number of nearest neighbors used by the model. In preparation for building a random forest model, we looked at how well a single decision tree, "DTR," could predict before building a random forest model "RFR" after tuning several parameters simultaneously use K-fold validation. From those models, we have the following mean squared errors (on the training data) and test MSE on the test dataset.

The goal of the analysis was to find a way to predict the number of rings in the abalone shell, which gives a way to determine the age of the abalone. As another test, we can ask how often our models correctly predict the true age of the abalone. Because I was curious, I also looked at how accurate the models were if we only required the prediction, for which I used the rounded value of the regression prediction, to be within one ring of the true number of rings, or possibly within two of the true number. Here are the accuracy figures for the models.

In [45]:
# Accuracy computations - linear regression
yp = np.round(yp_lm)
exact_lm = np.mean((yp == yte))
one_lm = np.mean(abs(yp - yte) <= 1)
two_lm = np.mean(abs(yp - yte) <= 2)
# Accuracy computations - KNN
yp = np.round(yp_knn)
exact_knn = np.mean((yp.reshape(1,-1) == yte))
one_knn = np.mean(abs(yp.reshape(1,-1) - yte) <= 1)
two_knn = np.mean(abs(yp.reshape(1,-1) - yte) <= 2)
# Accuracy computations - Decision Tree Regressor
yp = np.round(yp_dtr)
exact_dtr = np.mean((yp.reshape(1,-1) == yte))
one_dtr = np.mean(abs(yp.reshape(1,-1) - yte) <= 1)
two_dtr = np.mean(abs(yp.reshape(1,-1) - yte) <= 2)
# Accuracy computations rfr
yp = np.round(yp_rfr)
exact_rfr = np.mean((yp.reshape(1,-1) == yte))
one_rfr = np.mean(abs(yp.reshape(1,-1) - yte) <= 1)

We see that for this data set, only minor improvements in accuracy are obtained by using more complicated models. One thing worth noting is that KNN and linear regression were both fitted without categorical variable 'Sex'. If that characteristic is hard to measure, I would recommend the KNN model. Otherwise, the model choice would depend on the researchers needs. Also, I only perfunctorily tuned the KNN model, assuming random forests would be more accurate. It is possible that with more tuning, the KNN model would outperform the other models.
